article.description: The New York Liberty won their season-best fifth-straight game, defeating the Connecticut Sun, who lost at home for only the second time this season.
article.headline: Liberty win season-best fifth in a row
article.linkText: Liberty set down Sun, close in on playoff berth
article.story:
UNCASVILLE, Conn. (AP) -- Cathrine Kraayeveld is peaking at the
right time for the New York Liberty.

The rookie out of Oregon scored a career-high 14 points that
included a key 3-pointer late in the game to lead the Liberty to a
64-58 win over the Connecticut Sun on Saturday.

The win extended the Liberty's season-best win streak to five
and moved them a half-game behind second-place Indiana.

"I'm just trying to do what the coaches tell me to do. Set
screens, shoot the 3," Kraayeveld said. "I'm not trying to do
anything special."

It was the Liberty's third game without All-Star Ann Wauters,
out with a broken hand, and the 6-foot-4 Kraayeveld has been
helping fill the void in her absence. The Liberty signed Kraayeveld
July 1 after San Antonio placed her on waivers and in the last
three games, she's put up career numbers.

"She fits into our system well and that is why we picked her
up," Liberty coach Pat Coyle said. "We've been lucky. You can't
replace Ann Wauters but what you get off the bench with Cathrine
and (La'Keshia) Frett is what makes the difference."

Liberty forward Elena Baranova grabbed 18 rebounds, also a
personal best.

It was a rare home defeat for the league-leading Sun (24-7), who
have lost only twice at the Mohegan Sun arena this season. The loss
also snapped their six-game streak.

New York (18-13) dominated from the outside, hitting a
franchise-best 12 3-pointers. Kraayeveld was 4-of-7 from the
perimeter, none bigger than her 3 with 1:54 left to give New York a
60-55 lead.

Baranova finished with 11 points and Crystal Robinson and Becky
Hammon had 10 apiece.

Lindsay Whalen led the Sun with 22 points and Asjha Jones had
16. Taj McWilliams-Franklin pulled down a team-high 11 rebounds.
Team scoring leader Nykesha Sales struggled on offense and was
1-of-6 from the field for two points.

"It was one of those days," Sales said. "New York is a very
hungry team and they were hitting their shots."

Leading 28-23 at the break, the Liberty kicked off the second
half with a 9-2 run with -- what else -- a 3-pointer. Hammon hit from
the perimeter to begin the run and New York withstood a couple
Connecticut runs down the stretch to seal the win.

Connecticut got within two points twice in the final three
minutes but each time the Liberty had an answer.

"When you shoot as bad as we did, you don't give yourself a
chance to win," Connecticut coach Mike Thibault said. "We had one
starter in double figures. Without (Ann) Wauters, they played a lot
differently. They played all small people out on the perimeter."

New York opened the game with four straight 3s from four
different players in the first six minutes and were quickly out to
an 18-5 lead.

Connecticut got its first basket with 17:25 left,
McWilliams-Franklin's layup, and missed their next 12 shots.

The Sun climbed back in it with defense and personnel changes.
Thibault inserted defensive specialist Brooke Wyckoff for 7-foot-2
Margo Dydek, who was making her first start since leaving the team
10 days ago to compete with her Polish national team in the
European Championship qualifiers. The smaller, speedier lineup
forced the Liberty into seven turnovers and Connecticut responded
with a 13-2 run.

Whalen's breakaway layup off a Wyckoff steal gave Connecticut
its first lead at 22-20 with 3:06 left to play. But after a pair of
Sun turnovers Baranova and Crystal Robinson hit consecutive 3s down
the stretch.

"We just stepped up and took the shots we could make," Hammon
said. "We have shooters on this team and Cathrine got the bulk of
those."
